revision.text:
{{Infobox person |name = Ali Puli |image = Alipuli.png |image_size = 150px |caption = 18th Century depiction of Ali Puli by Burghard de Groot |birth_name = |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = Not Specified |death_cause = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = |residence = |nationality = [[Mauretania]]n |known_for = [[Hermeticism|Hermetic Philosopher]] and attributed author of ''Centrum Naturae Concentratum'' |education = |alma_mater = |employer = |occupation = [[Alchemy|Alchemist]] |home_town = |title = |salary = |networth = |height = |weight = |term = |predecessor = |successor = |party = |boards = |spouse = |partner = |children = |parents = |relatives = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }} '''Ali Puli''', also known as '''Alipili''', is the attributed author of a number of 17th-century [[alchemy|alchemical]] and [[hermeticism|hermetic]] texts. However, his historical existence is doubtful, and [[A.E. Waite]] went as far as to describe the work attributed to him as "forgery pure and simple in respect of age and authorship [which] may be left to stand at its value in the matter of content."<ref name=waite1>{{cite book|pages=352–7|first=A.E.|last=Waite|title=The Secret Tradition in Alchemy, its development and records|publisher=K. Paul, Trench, Trubner & Co., Ltd.|location=London|year=1926|oclc=1295967}}</ref>
He is described as a [[Mauretania]]n [[Christianity|Christian]] of [[Asia]]tic extraction - also variously as an [[Arab]] (because he was said to have written in [[Arabic]]), and a [[Moors|Moor]].<ref name=waite2>{{cite journal|last=Waite|first=A.E.|title=Some notes on the alchemist Alipili|journal=The Alchemical Journal |date=November 1914 |volume=3|issue=15 |pages=25–28|oclc=41963988}}</ref>
==Influence== The most influential work attributed to him is ''Centrum Naturae Concentratum''. This work was purported to have been written originally in Arabic, though no Arabic version is extant. It was published in Dutch in 1694, and first translated into English by [[Edmund Brice]] in 1696. It is most noted for the following passage:
{{Quote|I admonish thee, whosoever thou art, that desirest to dive into the innermost parts of Nature, if that thou seekest thou findeth not within thee, thou wilt never find it without thee.<ref name=alipili1>{{cite book|year=1696|place=London|publisher=J.Harris|translator=E. Brice|title=Centrum naturae concentratum,or, The salt of nature regenerated|last=Alipili|oclc=13046722}}</ref>}}
This passage is cited by Waite as evidence of a spiritual mystical tradition within alchemy, and has been widely quoted, notably by the [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophist]] [[Madame Blavatsky]] (who misattributes him as Abipili).<ref name=isis1>{{cite book|last=Blavatsky|first=H.P.|title=Isis Unveiled|page=617|volume=Vol.2|url=http://www.theosociety.org/pasade/isis/iu2-12b.htm|place=New York NY|year=1972|origyear=1877|isbn=1-55700-135-9|publisher=Theosophical University Press Online Edition|oclc=310905077}}</ref>
The passage has been identified as a source of the [[Wicca]]n ''[[Charge of the Goddess]]'' produced by [[Gerald Gardner (Wiccan)|Gerald Gardner]] and later revised by [[Doreen Valiente]].<ref name="serith1">{{cite web|url=http://www.ceisiwrserith.com/wicca/charge.htm|first=Ceisiwr|last= Serith|title=The Sources of the Charge of the Goddess|accessdate =23 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928211209/http://www.ceisiwrserith.com/wicca/charge.htm| archivedate= 28 September 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> It is the oldest of the sources so identified.
