'''John Davies''' (13 November 1787 &ndash; 27 April 1855) was a Welsh ([[Glamorganshire]]) stone mason, and a composer. He began his career as a stone-mason, notoriously working by both day and night. He had been taught to play the dulcimer by a lodger at the age of about fourteen, but it was not until he was about thirty that he seriously began to study music, becoming both a performer and a composer.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Maggie Humphreys|author2=Robert Evans|title=Dictionary of Composers for the Church in Great Britain and Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WSLUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88|year=1997|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-0-7201-2330-2|pages=88–}}</ref>

His works include a number of anthems and hymn tunes, such as "Gethsemane" (''Lleuad yr Oes'', 1827), which was arranged by Rowland Huw Pritchard.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Davies|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-PRIC-HUW-1811.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|last=Griffith|first=Robert David|accessdate= 2 July 2017}}</ref>

He died in 1855 in [[Llanelli]], and was buried in [[Mynydd-bach]] cemetery. 
<ref>{{cite web|title=John Davies|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-JOH-1787.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|last=Williams|first=Griffith John|accessdate= 20 June 2017}}</ref>

