The '''Pulahan''' (literally "those wearing red"; [[Plural|pl]]: '''Pulahanes'''; {{lang-es|Pulajan}}), also known as '''Dios-Dios''', are the members of a [[revivalism|religious revival]] of [[Philippine mythology|Philippine beliefs]] that developed in the [[Visayas]] prior to the [[Philippine Revolution]]. At its peak, it numbered around 10,000–15,000 adherents. The movement was severely crippled during the [[Philippine Revolution]] after the [[Philippine Constabulary]] took over patrols in [[Samar (island)|Samar]], when the [[U.S. military]] declared the island as "pacified".

==Beliefs==
Pulahanes practiced a [[syncretism|syncretic]] religious revival centered mostly on [[Philippine mythology]] and [[Folk Catholicism]]. Individual beliefs include the [[Agimat|anting-antings]] as well as the revival of the [[babaylan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bac/2006/11/04/oped/gil.alfredo.severino.think.economics.html |title=Severino: Cinco de Noviembre: Revolution or Hacienda? |publisher=Sun.Star Bacolod |date=2006-11-04 |accessdate=2010-03-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211152844/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bac/2006/11/04/oped/gil.alfredo.severino.think.economics.html |archivedate=2008-12-11 |df= }}</ref> Indigenous fighting techniques such as [[eskrima]] were also utilized in the elite and ferocious combat style.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olaa-naloeskrima.com/articles/DerobioEscrimaHistoryInfo.htm |title=Ola`a-Nalo Eskrima |publisher=Ola`a-Nalo Eskrima |date=1992-07-29 |accessdate=2010-03-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905195445/http://www.olaa-naloeskrima.com/articles/DerobioEscrimaHistoryInfo.htm |archivedate=2012-09-05 |df= }}</ref> They practiced a form indigenous [[martial arts]] called Derobio Eskrima and they specialize using a heavy, crescent-shaped [[bolo knife]] in their battles. Religious rituals using bottles of [[Holy Oil (Christianity)|holy oil]], prayer books such as the [[Bible]], consecrated ''[[anting-anting]]'', as blessings before battles.

[[United States|American]]s have described Pulahanes as notorious fighters and are experts in hand-to-hand combat. [[Battle cry|War cries]] were also common among their fighters. They have also been described as lacking in strategy due to their high casualty figures in battles such as the [[Massacre at Dolores]]. They were the subject of many laws passed during the early [[History of the Philippines (1898–1946)|American colonial period]] and have often been accused of [[banditry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bwa-baptist-heritage.org/phil-Pas.htm |title=A History of Philippine Baptist Pastors 1898-2002 |publisher=Bwa-baptist-heritage.org |date=1983-08-29 |accessdate=2010-03-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914035730/http://www.bwa-baptist-heritage.org/phil-Pas.htm |archivedate=2009-09-14 |df= }}</ref>

